\title{A Numerical Observation on the Koide Combination for the $(c, b, t)$ Quark Triple at \texorpdfstring{$\mu = m_\tau$}{mu = m\_tau}}
\author{Andrew M. Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 14, 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m)/(\sum \sqrt{m})^2$ takes the value $2/3$ for the charged leptons to one part in $10^5$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}, an empirical regularity for which no derivation has been accepted. Extensions to the quark sector have been examined in the literature, most directly by Rivero \citep{Rivero2011}. In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported that the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating charged-lepton triple matches the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the lepton-sum scale within current FLAG lattice precision.

The present note reports a related descriptive numerical observation on the heavy quark Koide combination $Q(c, b, t)$, together with a within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription robustness test that constitutes the central empirical content of the paper.

\paragraph{Observation under one specific prescription.} We compute $Q(c, b, t)$ in $\overline{\text{MS}}$ at $4$-loop with $m_c$ run from its self-scale to a variable $\mu$, $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t$ at $m_t(m_t)$ (call this $P_0$). At $\mu = m_\tau$ the result is $0.666718$ against $2/3 = 0.666667$, a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$. The propagated input uncertainty is $\sigma_Q^{\text{input}} \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, dominated by the PDG uncertainty on $m_t$. The $4$-loop perturbative truncation uncertainty, estimated from the $|4L - 3L|$ residual shift, is approximately $1.39 \times 10^{-4}$, which is approximately $2.7$ times \emph{larger} than the residual itself; the perturbative series has not converged at the residual scale. The residual is therefore consistent with exact closure, with a perturbative artifact of unconverged $4$-loop running, and with input-precision noise; we cannot distinguish these possibilities at present input and computational precision.

\paragraph{Within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription robustness test (partial null result).} We test whether the closure persists under four alternative within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions: ($P_1$) all three masses evaluated at a common scale $\mu$; ($P_2$) running $m_b$ instead of $m_c$; ($P_3$) running $m_t$ instead; ($P_4$) running $m_c$ and $m_b$ together. \textbf{Of the five prescriptions tested ($P_0$ through $P_4$), only $P_0$ produces a zero crossing of $Q - 2/3$ near $m_\tau$.} Under $P_1$ (common-scale evaluation), $Q$ is approximately constant at $0.7192$ across the entire perturbative range and never crosses $2/3$ at any scale. Under $P_2$, $P_3$, and $P_4$, zero crossings exist but occur at $6.25$~GeV, $96.9$~GeV, and $2.95$~GeV respectively --- none within $1$~GeV of any charged lepton mass. The closure at $m_\tau$ is therefore prescription-specific within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, not a feature of the underlying mass spectrum in any prescription-independent sense. We report this as a partial null result on the prescription independence of the closure: the closure exists under $P_0$, it does not exist under any of the four within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ alternatives we tested, and we cannot defend $P_0$ as a uniquely privileged prescription on the basis of the data.

\paragraph{What this paper is, and is not.} This is a descriptive numerical observation paired with a robustness check. We do not present it as a discovery, as a hypothesis test, or as a frequentist significance claim. All masses are $\overline{\text{MS}}$ throughout (one mass-renormalization scheme, no scheme mixing); the prescription scan in this paper is a within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ scan, not a cross-scheme scan. Robustness across alternative renormalon-improved schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) is acknowledged as a separate methodological limitation that we have not addressed. The observed closure at $m_\tau$ under $P_0$ is consistent with several interpretations the data cannot distinguish: a structural feature of the heavy quark mass spectrum visible only under $P_0$, an artifact of unconverged $4$-loop running, a coincidence within a convention-dependent construction, or a feature of the post-hoc search procedure by which it was found. We make no claim of significance, mechanism, derivation, or universal pattern. We report the observation and the robustness null result so that future work --- improved input precision on $m_t$, computation at higher loop orders, cross-scheme verification, and tests on independent quark triples --- has a documented baseline against which to compare.

\smallskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Koide relation; heavy quark masses; charm mass; $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running; four-loop QCD; prescription robustness; numerical observation; lepton-derived scales
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

The Koide relation \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \equiv \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide_lepton}
\end{equation}
holds for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$ and has resisted derivation for over four decades. Extensions to the quark sector have been attempted from several directions. Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} reported the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ closing to approximately $2\%$ and developed the chained-Koide ``waterfall'' construction over sequential heavy triples. Symmetry-based approaches have been pursued by Sumino \citep{Sumino2009} via family gauge symmetry. Geometric reformulations via the Descartes circle theorem appear in Kocik \citep{Kocik2012} and were extended to the lepton-Soddy construction in our companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026}. A neutrino-sector extension has been discussed by Brannen \citep{Brannen2006} and others \citep{RodejohannZhang2011,Krolikowski2014}. We treat \eqref{eq:koide_lepton} as an empirical input throughout this note.

\paragraph{The companion observation.} In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we examined the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F} \equiv k_4^-$ of the Koide-saturating charged-lepton Descartes configuration and reported that $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV is numerically consistent with the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau = 1883.0$~MeV within current FLAG lattice precision (residual $+0.042$~MeV against a dominant lattice uncertainty of $\pm 0.69$~MeV). That observation involved a lepton-derived quantity matching a quark mass at a lepton-derived scale.

\paragraph{The present note.} The present note reports a paired result on the heavy quark Koide combination $Q(c,b,t)$. We tested whether this combination produces a closure to $2/3$ under any of five within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions for evaluating the three masses at different RG points. \textbf{Of the five prescriptions tested, only one produces a closure of $Q$ near $m_\tau$, and that prescription is an arbitrary within-scheme choice we cannot defend on principled grounds.} Under that prescription --- which we label $P_0$, with $m_c$ run via four-loop QCD to $\mu = m_\tau$ and $m_b$, $m_t$ held at their tabulation self-scales --- the combination takes a value within $\sim 5 \times 10^{-5}$ of $2/3$, approximately one order of magnitude smaller than the propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q$, with a zero crossing of $(Q - 2/3)$ within tens of MeV of $m_\tau$. Under each of the four alternative within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions tested, no closure near any lepton mass exists. We characterize both the $P_0$ observation and the prescription robustness null result, decompose the uncertainty, and make explicit a long list of things we do not claim.

\paragraph{What this paper is.} This is a descriptive numerical observation report. We do not test a hypothesis in the formal frequentist sense. We do not compute $p$-values or significance levels. We do not present pre-registered predictions. The observation was found post-hoc within an implicit search whose effective size we cannot rigorously bound; we disclose the discovery chronology in Section~\ref{sec:disclosure} and we make the methodological limitations explicit in Section~\ref{sec:caveats}. We provide the descriptive material a reader needs to evaluate the observation on its own terms, and we leave the question of whether it constitutes evidence for any physical interpretation to the reader.

\paragraph{Why we report it, and what we report alongside it.} Two features distinguish the observation from a generic numerical coincidence at first reading. First, the closure occurs near a named lepton mass ($m_\tau$), specifically the same lepton-derived scale family ($\{m_\tau, \Sigma m_\ell\}$) that appeared in the companion note's $m_s$ observation. Second, of five particle-derived natural scale candidates in the perturbative regime tested in Section~\ref{sec:alt_scales} ($\Sigma m_\ell$, $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, $M_Z$, $m_t(m_t)$), $m_\tau$ produces the smallest absolute residual by approximately one order of magnitude over the next-best candidate. \textbf{Neither feature constitutes statistical evidence in the inferential sense.} Most importantly, in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} we test the closure under four alternative within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions and show that it does not survive any of them: only the $P_0$ prescription (run $m_c$ to $\mu$, hold $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their self-scales) produces a closure near a lepton mass. The closure is therefore prescription-specific within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, and any interpretation as a feature of the underlying mass spectrum requires defending the choice of $P_0$ as a privileged prescription, which we do not attempt. We report both the observation and the prescription robustness null result so that the reader has the complete descriptive picture, with all of the interpretive limitations made explicit in Section~\ref{sec:caveats}.

\paragraph{Organization.} Section~\ref{sec:setup} fixes notation, scheme, and inputs. Section~\ref{sec:observation} reports the central observation with its full propagated uncertainty budget and continuous scale dependence. Section~\ref{sec:alt_scales} compares the closure across five particle-derived natural scale candidates and two human-chosen conventional reference scales. Section~\ref{sec:robustness} reports the within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription robustness test, which is the empirically central piece of the paper. Section~\ref{sec:disclosure} discloses the discovery chronology and the bounds of the implicit search space. Section~\ref{sec:caveats} states the methodological limitations and non-claims explicitly, including the conceptual issues that prevent the observation from supporting an inferential significance interpretation. Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses sensitivity to future input-precision improvements and the relationship to prior work.


\section{Setup and Notation}
\label{sec:setup}

We work in the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme throughout for the quark masses. Input central values and their uncertainties:

\begin{itemize}
\item $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$ \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$ \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV ($\overline{\text{MS}}$, derived from the PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} top-quark pole mass $m_t^{\text{pole}} = 172.57 \pm 0.29$~GeV via the four-loop pole-to-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ conversion \citep{Marquard2015} as implemented in \texttt{CRunDec}). We acknowledge a tension in this choice: we use a top-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass derived by perturbative conversion from a pole-mass extraction, while we argue elsewhere in this paper that pole masses are conceptually problematic at the precision level we care about (see the renormalon discussion in Section~\ref{sec:setup} below). This is a common phenomenological practice in heavy-quark mass arithmetic --- direct $\overline{\text{MS}}$ extractions of $m_t$ from cross-section measurements exist but have larger published uncertainties than the converted pole-mass value --- but the tension is real and we note it here rather than hiding it. The $0.7$~GeV uncertainty already includes a conservative allowance for conversion uncertainty by community convention; a more aggressive accounting that adds an additional $\sim 200$~MeV renormalon-induced ambiguity in quadrature would inflate $\sigma(m_t^{\overline{\text{MS}}})$ to $\sim 0.73$~GeV, a small effect on $\sigma_Q$ that does not change any qualitative conclusion in this paper
\item $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ \citep{PDG2024}
\item $m_e = 0.5109989461$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6583755$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV \citep{PDG2024}
\end{itemize}

All three heavy quark masses are $\overline{\text{MS}}$ quantities. \textbf{We use a single scheme throughout: $\overline{\text{MS}}$.} The three masses are evaluated at three different RG points \emph{within} $\overline{\text{MS}}$ --- $m_c$ at the variable scale $\mu$, $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t$ at $m_t(m_t)$. This is the standard convention by which heavy quark masses are quoted in PDG and FLAG tables, where each heavy quark mass is reported at its own self-scale because the perturbative series defining the running converges fastest there. Quoting $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b)$ and $m_t$ at $m_t(m_t)$ in the same expression is not scheme mixing; it is the standard tabulation convention applied to two masses simultaneously, with both tabulations in the same scheme.

We use $\overline{\text{MS}}$ rather than the pole-mass scheme because the heavy-quark pole mass is not well-defined at the precision of our observation: the perturbative series defining the pole mass suffers from infrared renormalon ambiguities of order $\Lambda_{\text{QCD}} \sim 200\text{--}500$~MeV \citep{BigiShifman1994,Beneke1998}, several orders of magnitude larger than the residual reported in this paper. The $\sim 10$~GeV difference between $m_t^{\text{pole}} \approx 172.5$~GeV and $m_t^{\overline{\text{MS}}}(m_t) \approx 162.5$~GeV is itself an artifact of this ambiguity, not a physical disagreement. $\overline{\text{MS}}$ is the only scheme in which $10^{-4}$-precision heavy-quark mass arithmetic is well-defined; we make the choice on physics grounds, not because alternative choices were tested and rejected. We discuss the question of \emph{other} renormalon-improved schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) as a methodological limitation in Section~\ref{sec:caveats}: those schemes would in principle also be acceptable, and a future cross-scheme robustness check is left to future work.

The single element the observation varies, within this single-scheme setup, is the choice of which RG point to evaluate $m_c$ at.

Running between scales is performed via four-loop QCD using \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec}, with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$, giving active-flavor regions $n_f \in \{3, 4, 5, 6\}$. \textbf{The reference computation throughout this paper uses 4-loop running.} The 5-loop coefficients are used in one place only --- the loop-order progression of Section~\ref{sec:error_budget}, where they enter the truncation uncertainty estimate via the $|5L - 4L|$ residual shift --- and are not used for the central numerical values quoted elsewhere. The truncation uncertainty estimator we use as the principal estimate is $|4L - 3L|$, which is the more conservative of the two available shift estimators ($|4L - 3L| = 1.39 \times 10^{-4}$ versus $|5L - 4L| = 3.27 \times 10^{-5}$); we choose the conservative estimator because the perturbative series has not demonstrably converged at this precision and the more conservative estimate is the honest one. For each evaluation of $m_c$ at a scale $\mu \neq m_c(m_c)$, $m_c$ is run from its self-scale to $\mu$ under the appropriate $n_f$ region. The Koide combination is then evaluated as
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)(\mu) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_c(\mu) + m_b(m_b) + m_t(m_t)}{\left(\sqrt{m_c(\mu)} + \sqrt{m_b(m_b)} + \sqrt{m_t(m_t)}\right)^2},
\label{eq:Q_def}
\end{equation}
where only $m_c$ carries a $\mu$-dependence; $m_b$ and $m_t$ are evaluated at their tabulated self-scale values $m_b(m_b) = 4.203$~GeV and $m_t(m_t) = 162.5$~GeV from FLAG and PDG respectively. \textbf{Note on the multi-scale evaluation within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.} We want to be unambiguous about what \eqref{eq:Q_def} is and is not. It is a single algebraic combination of three $\overline{\text{MS}}$ masses, all in the same scheme, with each mass evaluated at one specific RG point within that scheme. The three RG points happen to differ from one another (because the standard tabulation convention quotes each heavy quark mass at its own self-scale), but this is multi-scale evaluation \emph{within} $\overline{\text{MS}}$, not a mixing of schemes. There is no pole mass anywhere in this paper; there is no on-shell mass anywhere in this paper; there is no scheme other than $\overline{\text{MS}}$ anywhere in this paper.

The combination is not RG-invariant: its numerical value depends on which RG point one chooses for $m_c$, which is the very freedom the observation is exploring. We will refer to this as \emph{scale-prescription dependence} (the dependence on which mass one chooses to evaluate at which scale within the single scheme), not as \emph{scheme dependence} (which would refer to a choice between different mass-renormalization schemes). The two are distinct concepts and we want to keep them distinct throughout the paper. The scale-prescription dependence is the content of the observation, not a methodological problem; the question being asked is precisely whether one specific prescription (run $m_c$ to $\mu = m_\tau$) produces a closure to $2/3$ that other prescriptions do not.

A second important interpretive consequence: the existence of a $\mu$ at which $Q(c, b, t)(\mu)$ takes any specific rational value within the range of the curve is mathematically generic for a continuous function whose range spans the target value across the perturbative window. The interest in the present observation, if any, lies not in the existence of such a crossing but in its specific location near $m_\tau$ and its numerical character relative to the propagated uncertainty.

We use the term \emph{closure} throughout to refer to the numerical proximity of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ to $2/3$ at a chosen $\mu$, without implying that the proximity carries any inferential significance.


\section{The Observation}
\label{sec:observation}

At the central input values and $\mu = m_\tau$:
\begin{equation}
m_c(m_\tau) = 1.14262~\text{GeV}, \qquad Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 0.666717692.
\label{eq:headline}
\end{equation}
The residual against $2/3$ is
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} - \frac{2}{3} \;=\; +5.10 \times 10^{-5}.
\label{eq:residual}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Input uncertainty decomposition}
\label{sec:error_budget}

We propagate each input uncertainty independently through the four-loop running and Koide combination to obtain the contribution of each source to $\sigma_Q$ at $\mu = m_\tau$. Table~\ref{tab:budget} shows the decomposition.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution to $Q$ & Fraction of total variance \\
\midrule
FLAG $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV & $4.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & 0.65\% \\
FLAG $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV & $1.82 \times 10^{-4}$ & 12.8\% \\
PDG $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV & $4.73 \times 10^{-4}$ & 86.4\% \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & $1.78 \times 10^{-4}$ & (separate) \\
Four-loop truncation $|4L - 3L|$ shift & $1.39 \times 10^{-4}$ & (dominant after $m_t$) \\
Five-loop truncation $|5L - 4L|$ shift & $3.27 \times 10^{-5}$ & ($\sim 1\%$) \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum (quark masses only) & $5.09 \times 10^{-4}$ & \\
Quadrature sum (including $\alpha_s$) & $5.39 \times 10^{-4}$ & \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Decomposition of $\sigma_Q$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ under independent variation of each input. The PDG uncertainty on $m_t$ dominates the input-precision budget. The four-loop truncation uncertainty, estimated as the absolute $|4L - 3L|$ residual shift computed from \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec}, is $1.39 \times 10^{-4}$ --- approximately $2.7$ times \emph{larger} than the observed residual of $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ at $4$-loop. The five-loop $|5L - 4L|$ shift drops to $3.27 \times 10^{-5}$ but the series cannot be claimed to have converged at the residual scale on the basis of one term. The truncation uncertainty therefore exceeds the residual itself, and any interpretation of the residual as a ``closure'' must be qualified accordingly. Input correlations among $m_c$, $m_b$, $m_t$, and $\alpha_s$ from shared lattice systematics and scheme-conversion uncertainties are not propagated.}
\label{tab:budget}
\end{table}

Combining the independent quark-mass contributions and $\alpha_s$ in quadrature gives a total propagated input uncertainty of $\sigma_Q^{\text{input}} \approx 5.39 \times 10^{-4}$. The observed residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ is approximately a factor of ten below this input-precision band. \textbf{However, the four-loop QCD truncation uncertainty, estimated as $|4L - 3L| = 1.39 \times 10^{-4}$, is approximately a factor of $2.7$ \emph{larger} than the residual.} Combining input precision and truncation in quadrature gives a total uncertainty $\sigma_Q^{\text{total}} \approx 5.57 \times 10^{-4}$, dominated still by $m_t$ but with truncation as the second-largest contribution. The ratio of residual to total uncertainty is approximately $1/11$. \textbf{This is a measurement-precision-and-perturbative-control statement, not a statistical significance statement, and the perturbative truncation alone exceeds the residual.} A residual smaller than total uncertainty is consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$, but it is also consistent with any other value within the band, and it is in particular consistent with the residual being a perturbative artifact of unconverged $4$-loop running rather than a feature of the underlying physics. Three further features of the budget deserve attention.

\paragraph{The $m_t$ uncertainty dominates.} The PDG uncertainty on the top quark contributes more than $86\%$ of the quark-mass variance on $Q$. The Koide combination weights the three masses in a way that makes $m_t$'s input uncertainty the rate-limiting factor, even though the scale scan varies $m_c$ rather than $m_t$. Future precision improvements on $m_t$ would tighten $\sigma_Q$ more than improvements on $m_c$ would.

\paragraph{Truncation uncertainty is comparable to the residual itself.} We compute the residual at each available QCD loop order using \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec}, which incorporates the $5$-loop QCD beta function and quark mass anomalous dimension coefficients of Baikov, Chetyrkin, and K\"uhn \citep{BaikovChetyrkinKuhn2017}. The full computation is implemented in \texttt{heavy\_koide\_loop\_order.py} in the accompanying repository \citep{RepoHeavy} and produces:
\begin{itemize}
\item 1-loop: $-2.0664 \times 10^{-3}$
\item 2-loop: $-5.0914 \times 10^{-4}$
\item 3-loop: $-8.7892 \times 10^{-5}$
\item 4-loop: $+5.1026 \times 10^{-5}$ \quad (reference value)
\item 5-loop: $+8.3674 \times 10^{-5}$
\end{itemize}
The progression is monotone in sign and the residual changes sign between $3$-loop and $4$-loop. The $4L-3L$ shift ($1.39 \times 10^{-4}$, taken as the difference of residuals) and the $5L-4L$ shift ($3.27 \times 10^{-5}$) are comparable in magnitude to the $4$-loop residual itself. \textbf{We do not claim that the perturbative series has converged at $4$-loop at the level of the residual.} The $4$-loop value is reported as the reference for consistency with standard practice in heavy-quark mass running; it is not a quantity for which a $10^{-5}$-level closure can be interpreted as physically meaningful in the absence of an independent estimate of higher-order coefficients. We discuss this further in Section~\ref{sec:caveats}.

\paragraph{Input correlations are not propagated.} The independent-Gaussian quadrature sum assumes that $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, $m_t(m_t)$, and $\alpha_s(M_Z)$ are uncorrelated. In reality these quantities are extracted with shared lattice systematics, shared $\alpha_s$ assumptions, and shared scheme-conversion uncertainties; the true covariance matrix would couple them. The propagated $\sigma_Q$ reported above is therefore an idealization, and a correlated propagation could shift it modestly in either direction. We have not computed the correlated version because the publicly available correlation matrices are partial; we note the limitation rather than pretending the independent-Gaussian model is exact.


\subsection{Continuous scale dependence}
\label{sec:continuous}

We compute $Q(c, b, t)(\mu)$ as a continuous function of the charm evaluation scale across $\mu \in [1.0, 10000]$~GeV using the precomputed running-mass lookup table (1022 scale points, logarithmically spaced). The lower endpoint at $\mu = 1$~GeV is the conventional lower edge of the perturbative regime for the charm sector; results within a few hundred MeV of this lower endpoint are quoted descriptively only and we make no perturbative-precision claims in that region. The full curve is smooth and monotonic on each side of a minimum located near $\mu = m_\tau$. The zero crossing of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3$, found by bisection on the smooth curve to a precision well below the propagated input uncertainty, lies at approximately
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star^{\text{crossing}} \;\approx\; 1.7695~\text{GeV},
\label{eq:crossing}
\end{equation}
which is approximately $7$~MeV below $m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV. We quote the crossing scale to four significant figures because the input precision on $m_\tau$ ($\sim 0.1$~MeV) and the propagated $\sigma_Q$-equivalent width on $\mu$ ($\sim 73$~MeV) bracket the meaningful precision range; quoting more digits would imply a precision the analysis does not support. Since $dQ/d\mu \approx 6.94 \times 10^{-3}~\text{GeV}^{-1}$ near the crossing, the shift in $Q$ induced by a $\sigma_Q$ shift in inputs corresponds to a $\mu$ shift of approximately $73$~MeV. The observed $7.3$~MeV offset is thus approximately a factor of ten smaller than this propagated width, on the same scale that the residual is a factor of ten smaller than $\sigma_Q$.

The width of the $\mu$-window around $m_\tau$ within which $|Q - 2/3|$ stays below various thresholds is:
\begin{itemize}
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-4}$: $\mu \in [1.76, 1.78]$~GeV, width $\approx 20$~MeV (1.1\% of $m_\tau$)
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 3 \times 10^{-4}$: $\mu \in [1.73, 1.81]$~GeV, width $\approx 80$~MeV (4.5\% of $m_\tau$)
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 5.1 \times 10^{-4} \approx \sigma_Q$: $\mu \in [1.70, 1.84]$~GeV, width $\approx 140$~MeV (7.9\% of $m_\tau$)
\end{itemize}
The $\sigma_Q$-equivalent window is approximately $140$~MeV wide. We note explicitly that the existence of a zero crossing of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3$ somewhere in the perturbative window is not surprising in itself: $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ is a smooth continuous function whose range over the perturbative window spans values both above and below $2/3$, so an intermediate-value-theorem crossing is mathematically generic. The descriptive interest, if any, lies in the location of the crossing relative to specific named scales, not in the existence of the crossing itself.


\section{Comparison Across Natural Scale Prescriptions}
\label{sec:alt_scales}

We compute $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ at five particle-derived natural scale candidates in the perturbative regime --- the three heavy-quark self-scales $\{m_c(m_c), m_b(m_b), m_t(m_t)\}$, the $Z$-pole scale $M_Z$, and the lepton-sum scale $\Sigma m_\ell$ --- plus the baseline $m_\tau$ for a total of six particle-derived scales. We also evaluate $Q$ at two non-particle ``conventional reference'' scales: $2$~GeV (the standard reference scale at which the lattice community quotes light quark masses) and $1.5$~GeV (an arbitrary round number at the midpoint of the charm-tau region). The two conventional scales are \emph{not} particle masses and are not derived from the Standard Model spectrum --- they are decimal-clean numbers chosen by humans for convenience --- and we mark them as such in Table~\ref{tab:alt_scales} with a dagger ($\dagger$). They are included for completeness so that a reader can see how the closure compares against typical lattice/phenomenology reference scales, not as natural alternatives in the same sense as the particle-derived scales. Table~\ref{tab:alt_scales} shows the result at the central input values.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Prescription & $\mu$ (GeV) & $Q(c, b, t)$ & $|Q - 2/3|$ \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\textit{Particle-derived natural scales}} \\
$\mu = m_\tau$ (baseline; charged tau lepton mass) & $1.77686$ & $0.6667177$ & $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ \\
$\mu = \Sigma m_\ell$ (charged-lepton mass sum) & $1.88303$ & $0.6674136$ & $7.47 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
