\section{Within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ Prescription Robustness}
\label{sec:robustness}

The observation reported in Section~\ref{sec:observation} uses one specific within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription: $m_c$ run from its self-scale to the variable $\mu$, with $m_b$ and $m_t$ held at their respective tabulation self-scales. We refer to this as $P_0$. Because $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ is not RG-invariant, a natural and important question is whether the closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ persists under alternative within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions, or whether it is specific to $P_0$. We test this directly.

\paragraph{The four alternative prescriptions tested.} We consider four within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ alternatives to $P_0$, all using the same $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme and the same $4$-loop running infrastructure:
\begin{itemize}
\item $P_1$ (\textit{common scale}): all three masses evaluated at the variable $\mu$. $m_c(\mu)$, $m_b(\mu)$, $m_t(\mu)$.
\item $P_2$ (\textit{run $m_b$ instead}): $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(\mu)$, $m_t(m_t)$.
\item $P_3$ (\textit{run $m_t$ instead}): $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, $m_t(\mu)$.
\item $P_4$ (\textit{run $m_c$ and $m_b$ together}): $m_c(\mu)$, $m_b(\mu)$, $m_t(m_t)$.
\end{itemize}
For each prescription we scan $\mu$ over the perturbative range $[1, 200]$~GeV, find any zero crossings of $Q(\mu) - 2/3$ by bisection, and tabulate $Q$ at six named particle scales. Results are in Table~\ref{tab:prescription_scan}.

