\paragraph{Interpretation: the closure is prescription-specific within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.} The result is unambiguous and important. The $P_0$ closure to $2/3$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ does not survive under any of the four alternative within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions we tested. Under $P_1$, the most natural and most physically motivated alternative (all three masses at the same RG point), $Q$ is approximately constant at $0.7192$ across the full perturbative range and never crosses $2/3$ at any scale. The near-constancy is the expected behavior: under common-scale evaluation, the Koide combination over three masses is approximately invariant under joint RG flow, with the small residual $\mu$-dependence ($\sim 10^{-6}$ across the perturbative range) coming from threshold-matching effects when $\mu$ crosses a quark threshold. We note explicitly that $P_1$ is not strictly RG-invariant once threshold matching is included; the small variations in Table~\ref{tab:prescription_scan} for $P_1$ across different scales reflect these threshold effects and not numerical noise. That the $(c, b, t)$ triple gives approximately $0.7192$ in $\overline{\text{MS}}$ at $4$-loop, approximately $8\%$ above $2/3$, is the relevant fact: the heavy quark mass spectrum, evaluated at a common scale within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, simply does not produce closure to $2/3$. Under $P_2$, $P_3$, and $P_4$, zero crossings exist (as is mathematically generic for any continuous function spanning the target value) but they occur at $2.95$~GeV, $6.25$~GeV, and $96.9$~GeV --- none within $1$~GeV of any charged lepton.

The honest reading of Table~\ref{tab:prescription_scan} is that \textbf{the closure at $m_\tau$ reported in Section~\ref{sec:observation} is a feature of the $P_0$ prescription specifically, not of the heavy quark mass spectrum in any prescription-independent sense.} The lepton-scale framing predicts that some prescription should produce a closure near a lepton-derived scale. We find that $P_0$ does so. The lepton-scale framing does not predict that this should be the unique prescription producing such a closure, nor does it predict why $P_0$ specifically should be privileged. We do not develop a defense of $P_0$ in this paper.

\paragraph{An after-the-fact physical observation about $P_0$ (post-hoc, not a defense).} \textbf{We want to be explicit at the outset of this paragraph: what follows is a post-hoc physical observation about why $P_0$ might be considered marginally less arbitrary than the other within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions, and we did not pre-register $P_0$ as the unique privileged prescription before running the calculation. The reader should treat this paragraph as background information about the construction, not as a defense of $P_0$ as a uniquely meaningful choice.} With that caveat stated explicitly, the observation is the following. Within the $(c, b, t)$ triple, $m_c$ is the unique mass whose self-scale ($m_c(m_c) \approx 1.28$~GeV) lies below $m_\tau$ ($1.78$~GeV) in the perturbative regime. Running $m_c$ \emph{upward} from $m_c(m_c)$ to $m_\tau$ involves a fractional shift of approximately $-10.78\%$ in a single $n_f = 4$ region with no threshold crossings. Running $m_b$ to $m_\tau$ would require running $m_b$ \emph{downward} from $m_b(m_b) = 4.20$~GeV across the bottom threshold, with a fractional shift of approximately $+22.58\%$. Running $m_t$ to $m_\tau$ would require running through both bottom and charm thresholds, with a fractional shift of approximately $+87.44\%$. Among the three single-mass-running prescriptions, $P_0$ is the unique one that does not require running a mass downward through a threshold or by a large fractional amount. \textbf{This observation does not constitute a derivation of $P_0$, a justification for preferring $P_0$, or a defense against the prescription-dependence finding of this section.} The closure remains prescription-specific in the empirical sense established by Table~\ref{tab:prescription_scan}, regardless of whether a reader finds the after-the-fact $m_c$-uniqueness argument compelling. We include the paragraph because the physical fact is true and may be relevant to future theoretical work attempting to derive the closure from first principles, not because it changes the empirical conclusion of the prescription scan.

\paragraph{What the robustness check did and did not show.} The check tested prescription independence within $\overline{\text{MS}}$. It did not test scheme independence (alternative renormalon-improved schemes 1S, PS, MSR, kinetic; see Section~\ref{sec:caveats}). It did not test the lepton-scale hypothesis on independent quark triples. It did not test alternative target rationals. It is a single specific test of a single specific assertion: ``the closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ is robust under within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription changes.'' That assertion is empirically false. The closure is prescription-specific. We report this as a partial null result alongside the original observation, and we believe it is the most important single piece of information in this paper.

\section{Disclosure of the Discovery Search}
\label{sec:disclosure}

We disclose the chronology of the discovery and the bounds of the implicit search space here so that the reader can place the observation within its discovery context. None of what follows is part of an inferential calculation; it is descriptive disclosure.

\paragraph{Algebraic form was fixed in advance.} The relation under examination is Koide's $Q = 2/3$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}, with all coefficients and exponents at their published values. We did not tune the coefficient $2/3$; we did not vary the form of the symmetric polynomial; we did not consider a parameterized exponent. The form was inherited from Koide 1981 and is unchanged.

\paragraph{Two explicit scale trials.} The author tested two evaluation scales for the charm mass within the $(c, b, t)$ triple before the present observation was in hand:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The first scale tested was $\Sigma m_\ell$, carried over from the companion note. The residual was $+7.47 \times 10^{-4}$, of the same sign and order as $\sigma_Q$. The positive residual suggested a slightly lighter scale would reduce it.
\item The second scale tested was $m_\tau$, the heaviest individual charged lepton, $\approx 106$~MeV below $\Sigma m_\ell$. The residual was $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, the value reported in this paper.
\end{enumerate}
The explicit number of scale trials performed during discovery was \textit{two}. No other scales or alternative triples were tested before this result; the broader scan in Table~\ref{tab:alt_scales} and the within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription robustness scan in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} were performed after the observation was in hand, for the purpose of characterizing the local landscape and testing prescription independence.

\paragraph{The implicit search was larger.} The explicit count of two trials is not the effective trial count, because the candidate set was bounded by prior internalized knowledge of the quark running-mass landscape. In the six weeks preceding the observation, the author assembled a precomputed table of four-loop running quark masses at standard reference scales (\texttt{quark\_running\_lookup.json} in the accompanying repository \citep{RepoHeavy}), originally for unrelated work. By the time of the present observation, candidate scales that would obviously fail had been eliminated from explicit consideration through familiarity with the table. The two scales explicitly tested were the two perturbative-regime lepton-derived candidates remaining after this implicit narrowing. \textbf{We cannot rigorously bound the effective size of this implicit search}, and we do not claim that the look-elsewhere correction appropriate to the observation is small. A reader applying a generous look-elsewhere correction to the observed residual is applying a correction we cannot defend against. The chronology disclosure is honest disclosure of the search procedure, not a defense of a small effective trial count.

\paragraph{The choice of $(c,b,t)$ within the heavy-quark triple landscape.} The choice of the $(c, b, t)$ triple specifically, rather than $(s, c, b)$ or another combination, was motivated by the observation that $m_c$ is the unique mass in $(c,b,t)$ whose self-scale ($1.28$~GeV) lies below $m_\tau$ ($1.78$~GeV) in the perturbative regime: running $m_c$ \emph{upward} to $m_\tau$ involves a fractional shift of $-10.78\%$ in a single $n_f = 4$ region with no threshold crossings. Running $m_b$ to $m_\tau$ would require running $m_b$ \emph{downward} from its self-scale, crossing the bottom threshold in the wrong direction, with a fractional shift of $+22.58\%$. Running $m_t$ to $m_\tau$ would require running through both bottom and charm thresholds, with a fractional shift of $+87.44\%$. The choice of $m_c$ as the mass to vary was therefore physics-constrained within the $(c,b,t)$ triple. We note that this argument constrains the choice of mass to vary \textit{within} the $(c,b,t)$ triple but does not constrain the choice of triple itself; that choice came from the implicit search across familiar triples and is not free of the search bound discussed above.


\section{Caveats, Non-Claims, and Methodological Limitations}
\label{sec:caveats}

We make the following caveats and non-claims explicit. They are organized in three groups: methodological limitations (which constrain what the present observation can support), explicit non-claims about the observation's content, and limits we have chosen not to attempt to overcome.

\subsection{Methodological limitations}

\paragraph{The combination $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ is scale-prescription dependent within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.} The combination in \eqref{eq:Q_def} evaluates three $\overline{\text{MS}}$ masses at three different RG points within the same scheme: $m_c$ at the variable $\mu$, $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t$ at $m_t(m_t)$. The combination is not RG-invariant: its numerical value depends on which mass is run, on which RG points are chosen for the other two, and on what truncation order is taken in the running. A different prescription within $\overline{\text{MS}}$---running $m_b$ instead of $m_c$, or evaluating all three masses at a common scale, or running $m_c$ to a different scale---would produce a different curve and a different crossing location. The observation reported here is conditioned on the specific within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription of running only $m_c$ and holding $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their tabulation self-scales, at $4$-loop. We do not claim that the observation reflects a prescription-independent feature of the mass spectrum.

\paragraph{Robustness across alternative renormalon-improved schemes is not yet tested.} The choice of $\overline{\text{MS}}$ over the pole-mass scheme is forced by renormalon ambiguities at the $200\text{--}500$~MeV level which would dominate any pole-mass evaluation; the choice is on physics grounds and is not testable. There exist, however, several alternative renormalon-improved heavy-quark mass schemes (the 1S scheme, the potential-subtracted (PS) scheme, the renormalon-subtracted (MSR) scheme, and the kinetic scheme) which are well-defined at our precision level and which would in principle each give a numerically distinct version of the same observation. We have not run the analysis in any of these alternative schemes. The result is conditioned on $\overline{\text{MS}}$ as the choice of scheme, with each mass at its own self-scale within that scheme as the choice of RG points. A future cross-scheme robustness check (running the same observation in 1S, PS, MSR, or kinetic with appropriate scheme-conversion uncertainties) would either strengthen or weaken the observation; we flag this as a real limitation rather than claiming the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ result is universal.

\paragraph{The existence of a crossing of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ through any rational target is mathematically generic.} $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ is a continuous function of $\mu$ on the perturbative range whose values span an interval. By the intermediate value theorem, for any rational $p/q$ inside this interval, there exists a $\mu$ at which $Q(c,b,t)(\mu) = p/q$. The existence of a crossing through $2/3$ specifically is therefore not by itself a physical statement: it is a consequence of $2/3$ lying inside the range of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ for the central inputs. The descriptive interest in the observation, if any, lies entirely in the location of the crossing relative to specific named scales, not in the fact that a crossing exists.

\paragraph{The closure is empirically prescription-specific within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.} Section~\ref{sec:robustness} demonstrates by direct computation that the closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ does not survive under any of the four alternative within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions tested ($P_1$ common-scale, $P_2$ run $m_b$, $P_3$ run $m_t$, $P_4$ run $m_c$ and $m_b$ together). The closure is therefore conditioned on the specific choice of $P_0$. We have not constructed a principled, pre-registered argument for why $P_0$ should be privileged among within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions; the descriptive physical argument given in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} (that $m_c$ is the unique mass in $(c,b,t)$ that runs upward to $m_\tau$ in a single $n_f = 4$ region with no threshold crossing) is post-hoc rationalization in the strict sense, even if it is physically reasonable.

\paragraph{Loop-order truncation is not negligible at the residual scale.} The $4$-loop and $5$-loop residuals are $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ and $+8.37 \times 10^{-5}$. The $4$-loop value, used as the reference, differs from the $3$-loop value by $1.39 \times 10^{-4}$, which is larger than the residual at $4$-loop. The perturbative series has not demonstrably converged at the residual scale, and we do not claim that the $4$-loop or $5$-loop value is the "true" all-orders value at $\mu = m_\tau$. A more conservative truncation uncertainty than the one we report in Table~\ref{tab:budget} (e.g., the full $4L$-$3L$ shift of $1.39 \times 10^{-4}$) would substantially exceed the residual itself, in which case the residual is not a meaningful indicator of any closure beyond the truncation uncertainty.

\paragraph{Input correlations are ignored.} The independent-Gaussian propagation of $\sigma_Q$ in Section~\ref{sec:error_budget} assumes uncorrelated inputs, which is not the case. We note this as a limitation rather than correcting it.

\paragraph{The implicit search bound cannot be characterized.} We disclose the discovery chronology in Section~\ref{sec:disclosure} but do not claim that the explicit two-trial count is the effective trial count. The implicit search across the running-mass landscape is real and we cannot bound it rigorously.

\subsection{Explicit non-claims}

\paragraph{Not a hypothesis test.} We do not present the observation as the result of a frequentist hypothesis test. We do not compute $p$-values, percentiles, or confidence intervals in the inferential sense. The propagated uncertainty $\sigma_Q$ in Section~\ref{sec:error_budget} is a measurement-precision quantity, not a frequentist confidence interval on a stochastically distributed parameter. The prescription robustness scan in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} is a single direct empirical test of prescription independence, with one specific assertion (``the closure is robust under within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription changes'') that the data falsify.

\paragraph{Not a significance claim.} The ratio of the residual to $\sigma_Q$ is approximately $0.1$. We do not interpret this as a measure of statistical significance. A residual smaller than the propagated uncertainty is consistent with a continuum of values within the band; it does not by itself indicate that any specific value is correct.

\paragraph{Not a discovery.} We do not present the observation as a discovery. Discoveries in particle physics involve frequentist significance levels, look-elsewhere corrections, and reproducibility across independent measurements. None of these elements is present here.

\paragraph{Not a derivation.} We have not derived $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or first-principles framework.

\paragraph{Not a prediction.} The observation is post-hoc. The masses $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, $m_t(m_t)$ were all established measurements at the time the observation was made. Calling the observation a "prediction" would misrepresent its epistemic status.

\paragraph{Not a derivation of why $\mu = m_\tau$.} The motivating heuristic---that $m_\tau$ is the heaviest charged lepton and sits in the $1$--$2$~GeV window where a lepton-derived scale is the natural candidate to bridge to the charm sector---is the reason $m_\tau$ was tested, not an explanation of why it produces the smallest residual among the candidates we tested. The question of why $m_\tau$ specifically (rather than another scale in the $1$--$2$~GeV range) is not answered here.

\paragraph{Not a mechanism.} We do not propose a flavor-symmetry mechanism, a matching condition, a unification embedding, or any other structural reason that would generate $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$.

\paragraph{Not a universal claim about quark Koide closures.} We have tested one triple, $(c,b,t)$, under one sign convention and one scale prescription. We do not claim that lepton-derived scales produce closures universally across quark sector Koide-type relations, and we do not claim that the present observation predicts the behavior of $(s,c,b)$ or any other triple.

\paragraph{Not independent of the companion note.} The companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported a related observation (lepton Soddy curvature matching $m_s$ at $\Sigma m_\ell$). The present observation involves the same lepton-derived scale family. The two observations are not statistically independent: they were generated by the same author from the same general motivation, and neither is a blind test of the other. We treat them as two related descriptive observations, not as cross-validating evidence.

\paragraph{Not a scale-prescription-invariant relation within $\overline{\text{MS}}$.} The closure as reported is specific to $\overline{\text{MS}}$ with $m_c$ run from its self-scale to $\mu = m_\tau$ and $m_b$, $m_t$ held at their respective self-scales. A different within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ choice (e.g., evaluating all three masses at a common scale, or running $m_b$ to some scale) would give a different value for the combination at any given $\mu$. We do not claim the observation is invariant under these choices. Pole-mass evaluation is excluded for the renormalon reasons given in Section~\ref{sec:setup} (this is not a scheme comparison); robustness against the four well-defined alternative renormalon-improved schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) is acknowledged as a future-work item in the methodological limitations subsection above.

\subsection{What we do not attempt}

We have not attempted to construct a frequentist test that would confer significance on the observation, because we do not believe such a test is available given the post-hoc, prescription-specific, mathematically generic nature of the construction. Earlier versions of this manuscript attempted such constructions (profile likelihood, Feldman-Cousins, severity, parametric bootstrap, tiered enumeration with empirical $p$-values, discrete neighborhood characterization); on review, we found these constructions to be inappropriate to the problem and have removed them. The honest description is the descriptive characterization in Sections~\ref{sec:observation} and \ref{sec:alt_scales}, paired with the prescription robustness null result of Section~\ref{sec:robustness}, not an inferential test result.

We have not attempted to predict the behavior of related triples or alternative scale prescriptions. The lepton-scale "hypothesis" implicit in the choice of $m_\tau$ is too informal to make falsifiable predictions in the strict sense, and we do not present it as a falsifiable framework. Future work that tests the lepton-scale idea on independent targets would constitute a more rigorous inquiry; we leave this to future work.


\section{Discussion and Outlook}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Sensitivity to future input precision.} The propagated uncertainty $\sigma_Q$ is dominated by $\sigma(m_t)$. A future-collider improvement in $\sigma(m_t)$ by a factor of $\sim 5$ (e.g., from an $e^+ e^-$ Higgs/top factory) would reduce $\sigma_Q$ from $\sim 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ to approximately $1.6 \times 10^{-4}$. At that precision, the present residual of $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ would still lie within the propagated uncertainty band, but the band would be approximately three times narrower. Whether the observation persists at improved precision is an empirical question that will be answered by future measurements; we do not present this as a "test" or "prediction" in the formal sense, but as the natural thing to watch as input precision improves. If the central value of the residual moves outside the shrinking band as $m_t$ precision improves, the observation is no longer consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$ at the new precision; if it remains within the band, the situation is unchanged in interpretation but more sharply characterized numerically.

\paragraph{Sensitivity to higher-order QCD running.} The truncation uncertainty estimated from the $4L$-$3L$ and $5L$-$4L$ shifts is comparable to the residual itself. A computation of the running at $5$-loop or higher with reduced truncation uncertainty (which would require improved knowledge of the higher-order QCD coefficients and their uncertainties) could either tighten the truncation budget below the residual or reveal that the residual is itself a perturbative artifact. We have computed the $5$-loop residual ($+8.37 \times 10^{-5}$) using the available coefficients; the loop-order progression is monotone in sign and the all-orders asymptote is not determined.

\paragraph{Relation to the companion note.} The companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported a lepton-Soddy curvature matching $m_s$ at the lepton-sum scale $\Sigma m_\ell \approx 1883$~MeV. The present observation involves a different mathematical operation (the Koide combination on a heavy quark triple) at a different lepton-derived scale ($m_\tau \approx 1777$~MeV) acting on a different quark mass ($m_c$ rather than $m_s$). The two observations share a feature---a lepton-derived scale in the $1.7$--$1.9$~GeV range entering the characterization of a quark-sector quantity---but they are not independent: they originate with the same author, the present observation was motivated by the companion note, and neither is a blind test of the other. We treat them as two related descriptive observations whose connection (if any) is an open question. A future independent observation testing the lepton-scale idea on a target the present author has not handled would be more informative about whether the pattern is real.

\paragraph{Relation to Rivero's $(s,c,b)$ construction.} Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} reported the $(s,c,b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ closing to $\sim 2\%$ in 2011 and developed the chained-Koide construction. The present observation is structurally different: a different triple ($(c,b,t)$ rather than $(s,c,b)$), a different sign convention (all positive), and a specific scale prescription ($P_0$, with $m_c$ run to $m_\tau$). We do not claim the present observation is structurally related to Rivero's, and we do not develop a unified framework here.

\paragraph{Conclusion.} We have reported a paired observation and prescription robustness test on the heavy quark Koide combination $Q(c,b,t)$.

The observation: in $4$-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ under prescription $P_0$ (run $m_c$ to $\mu$, hold $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their tabulation self-scales), $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 0.666718$ against $2/3 = 0.666667$, a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$. The propagated input uncertainty is $\sigma_Q^{\text{input}} \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ and the $4$-loop perturbative truncation uncertainty is approximately $1.39 \times 10^{-4}$, which is $2.7$ times larger than the residual itself. The residual is consistent with exact closure, with a perturbative artifact, and with input-precision noise; the present analysis cannot distinguish these.

The prescription robustness test: of five within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescriptions tested ($P_0$ baseline plus four alternatives), only $P_0$ produces a closure of $Q$ near $m_\tau$. Under $P_1$ (common-scale evaluation of all three masses at $\mu$), $Q$ is approximately constant at $0.7192$ across the entire perturbative range and never crosses $2/3$ at any scale. Under the other three prescriptions, crossings exist but occur at scales far from any charged lepton mass. The closure is therefore prescription-specific within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, and the data do not support an interpretation of the observation as a feature of the heavy quark mass spectrum that is independent of the prescription choice.

We make no claim of significance, mechanism, or universal pattern. We do not defend $P_0$ as a uniquely privileged prescription on the basis of the data; the physical argument for $P_0$ given in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} (that $m_c$ is the unique mass in the triple that runs upward to $m_\tau$ in a single $n_f = 4$ region) is post-hoc rationalization in the strict sense. The construction is scale-prescription dependent within $\overline{\text{MS}}$, the existence of a crossing of $Q$ through any rational target on its range is mathematically generic, the loop-order truncation exceeds the residual, robustness across alternative renormalon-improved schemes (1S, PS, MSR, kinetic) is not yet tested, and the implicit search behind the discovery cannot be rigorously bounded. We report the observation and the prescription null result so that future work --- improved input precision on $m_t$, computation at higher loop orders, cross-scheme verification, and tests on independent triples --- has a documented baseline against which to compare. The question of whether the $P_0$ closure reflects an underlying structural feature of the mass spectrum or a coincidence within a convention-dependent construction is open and is, in our view, not resolvable from the data alone at present input and computational precision.


\section*{Computational Note}
\label{sec:computational}

Central values, four-loop running, Koide combination evaluations, input-uncertainty propagation, scale scans, the natural-scale comparison table, and the within-$\overline{\text{MS}}$ prescription robustness scan are reproducible from the accompanying GitHub repository \citep{RepoHeavy}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running is performed via \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807$~GeV, $m_b(m_b) = 4.203$~GeV, and $m_t(m_t) = 162.5$~GeV. The loop-order progression is implemented in \texttt{heavy\_koide\_loop\_order.py} (1- through 5-loop) and the prescription robustness scan in \texttt{heavy\_koide\_prescription\_scan.py} (the $P_0$ through $P_4$ scan of Section~\ref{sec:robustness}). All output JSON files are archived at the cited commit hash. All input values are PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} and FLAG 2024 \citep{FLAG2024} central values at the time of computation. Total runtime is approximately five minutes on a laptop.


